'''Innovation Park''' at [[Pennsylvania State University]] is a [[business park|business]] and [[research park]] covering {{convert|118|acre|km2}} in [[State College, Pennsylvania]], adjacent to the Penn State campus near the junction of [[Interstate 99]] and [[U.S. Route 322 in Pennsylvania|U.S. Route 322]].

The university's trustees designated the area for a research park in 1989.<ref>Joyce Gannon, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=g9IwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6477,355943&dq=penn-state-research-park&hl=en "Penn State research park targets high-tech firms"], ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', June 3, 1991.</ref>  Initially known as the Penn State Research Park<ref>[http://www.collegian.psu.edu:8080/archive/2000/09/09-15-00tdc/09-15-00dnews-5.asp "Business park gets boost: Innovation Park was picked as a prime site for a technology business."] ''[[The Daily Collegian (Penn State)|The Daily Collegian]]'', September 15, 2000.</ref><ref>[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DT&s_site=centredaily&p_multi=DT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB96D475398FAB0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM "Innovation Park: Expected Slow, Steady Growth"], ''[[Centre Daily Times]]'', February 4, 2001. (pay site).</ref> and opened in 1994, its stated mission was to be the "place where collaboration between the University and private sector companies can grow,"<ref>''This is Penn State: An Insider's Guide to the University Park Campus'' ([[Penn State University Press]], 2006), {{ISBN|978-0-271-02720-3}}, p. 137. [https://books.google.com/books?id=njsImNDk_bIC&pg=PA137 Excerpt available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> and to facilitate the transfer of University-based knowledge "to the market place and to foster economic development".<ref>Catherine Chaput, ''Inside the Teaching Machine: Rhetoric and the Globalization of the U.S. Public Research University'' ([[University of Alabama Press]], 2008), {{ISBN|978-0-8173-1609-9}}, p. 206. [https://books.google.com/books?id=R_5ZlY4YvjAC&pg=PA206 Excerpt available] at [[Google Books]].</ref>  It was renamed Innovation Park at Penn State in July 2000.<ref>[http://www.psu.edu/ur/2000/bot13julname.html "New Name For PSU Research Park: Innovation Park At Penn State"], Penn State press release, July 13, 2000.</ref>

The area is the location of a number of university offices, the [[Penn State World Campus]], a conference center, and more than 25 private companies.  The production facilities of [[WPSU-TV]] and [[WPSU-FM]] moved there in 2005.<ref>Nancy Caronia, [http://business.highbeam.com/4841/article-1G1-140495579/looking-fine-40-new-facility-penn-state-public-broadcasting "Looking fine at 40 -- New facility for Penn State Public Broadcasting."], ''Government Video'', December 1, 2005 (pay site).</ref>

