'''Kamila Sidiqi''' is an Afghan entrepreneur, government official, and the subject of New York Times Bestseller ''[[The Dressmaker of Khair Khana]]''.

==Background==
{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2015}}
Sidiqi received her teaching certificate the same day the [[Taliban]] arrived in [[Kabul]], rendering her unable to work. Without any means of supporting her family, the then 19-year-old turned to dressmaking. With the help of her sisters, she opened a tailoring school in their home to teach women to sew and provide employment after their training was completed. The venture went on to employ nearly 100 of Sidiqi's neighbours without attracting the Taliban's attention.

==Career==
In 2004, following the fall of the Taliban, Sidiqi set up Kaweyan Business Development Services<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaweyan Business Development Services|url=http://kaweyanbds.com/|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> to bring business and leadership skills to women and men in remote rural communities and cities. In her role as CEO, Sidiqi travelled across a country where few women could venture without a male relative to escort them, and where aid workers often travel with armed guards or local police. Her aim was to train rural communities in the basics of entrepreneurship. Kaweyan BDS was Afghanistan’s first business development company run by a woman. It trained 5,000 people (70 percent of them women) in business and leadership.

Since 2014, Sidiqi has been on the board of NGO Hand in Hand Afghanistan (a part of the [[Hand in Hand International]] network),<ref>{{cite web|title=Hand in Hand International|url=http://www.handinhandinternational.org|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> an NGO that helps the rural poor in Afghanistan to turn their skills and potential into jobs. She provides strategic direction to the organization, which has trained 22,000 micro-entrepreneurs (mostly women) who have gone on to create over 8,000 businesses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hand in Hand Afghanistan Results|url=http://handinhand.org.af/updated-results/|website=Hand in Hand Afghanistan website|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>

Sidiqi is a founding member of Leading Entrepreneurs of Afghanistan Development(LEAD). She is also a member of a number of influential international women’s associations
including the  Steering Committee for the South Asia Women Entrepreneurs Symposium.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

In October 2014, she became the Deputy Chief of Staff for the President's office at Government of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

