A '''shōtengai''' (商店街) is a style of Japanese [[commercial district]] running along a certain street. Shōtengai often connect to the nearest train station.<ref>{{cite book |last=Imai |first=Heide |year=2017 |title=Tokyo Roji: The Diversity and Versatility of Alleys in a City in Transition |publisher=Routledge |page=62 |isbn=9781317363644}}</ref> Most suburbs and towns of Japan have shōtengai of varying size, and larger shōtengai may take the form of covered [[Arcade (architecture)|arcades]] that are blocked off to traffic.<ref>{{cite book |last=Anderson |first=Collin |year=2012 |title=Evolution of a Retail Streetscape: DP Architects on Orchard Road |publisher=Images Publishing |page=42 |isbn=9781864704624}}</ref> A typical shōtengai includes most of these:
* supermarkets and grocery shops * restaurants, cafés and [[kissaten]] * [[izakaya]] and [[snack bar]]s (Japanese-style pubs with mostly male clientele; usually run and/or staffed by women) * [[pachinko]] parlors * [[massage parlor]]s * [[Barber|barber shop]]s * [[Amusement arcade|game centers]] * [[post office]]s * book shops * clothes shops * [[convenience store]]s * [[kōban]], neighborhood police substations
==See also== * [[Bazaar]] * [[Commercial district]] * [[Souq]] * [[Mom and pop shop]] * [[Shopping district]]
